'''Kyadondo Rugby Club''' is a [[rugby union]] ground in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].
It was built in 2000. Facilities include main ground, a training pitch and a club house.<ref>[http://www.kyadondo.co.ug/Club Kyadondo Rugby Club - About us]</ref>
The ground is home to several club teams, among them [[Heathens RFC]], a leading rugby club in Uganda.<ref>The Observer, November 29, 2010: [http://www.observer.ug/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6212&Itemid=80 Utl Kobs, MTN Heathens’ contrasting story in rugby]</ref> It has also hosted home games of the [[Uganda national rugby union team]], but the [[Uganda Rugby Union]] is considering hosting games at the [[National Stadium (Uganda)|National Stadium]] or [[Nakivubo Stadium]] due to limited capacity of Kyadondo.<ref>New vision, March 31, 2010: [http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/30/714769 Namboole stadium to host rugby cranes]</ref>
The club has also been a concert venue, [[Beenie Man]] is among the high-profile performers.<ref>Daily Monitor, December 7, 2009: [http://www.monitor.co.ug/LifeStyle/Entertainment/-/812796/818562/-/view/printVersion/-/2q9adb/-/index.html Beenie Man exhilarates Kampala]</ref>
==July 2010 Kampala attacks== Kyadondo Rugby Club was one of the two scenes of the [[July 2010 Kampala attacks]].<ref>BBC News, July 12, 2010: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/10605457.stm Uganda's World Cup joy shattered by blasts]</ref> The second attack, consisting of two explosions in quick succession, occurred at {{Nowrap|11:18&nbsp;pm}} at Kyadondo Rugby Club, where state-run newspaper ''[[New Vision]]'' was hosting a screening of the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/10/10/725548 |title=33 die in Kampala bomb attacks |work=[[New Vision]] |date=11 July 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714023549/http://newvision.co.ug/D/10/10/725548 |archivedate=14 July 2010 |df= }}</ref> According to eyewitnesses, there was an explosion near the 90th minute of the match, followed seconds later by a second explosion that knocked out the lights at the field.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/africa/07/12/uganda.bombings/?hpt=T1 |title=Death toll rises to 64 in Uganda twin bombings |first=Faith|last=Karimi|publisher=CNN|date=12 July 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> An explosion went off directly in front of a large screen that was showing the telecast from South Africa,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/725545 |title=Over 40 die in Kampala bomb blasts |work=[[New Vision]] |date=12 July 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715054623/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/725545 |archivedate=15 July 2010 |df= }}</ref> killing 49 people. The discovery of a severed head and leg at the rugby field suggests that it was a [[suicide attack]] carried out by an individual.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hzHMeIMsFmUA1bDTDUdeL_hCMbjAD9GT7O700|title=64 die in bomb attacks in Uganda during World Cup|last=Kron|first=Josh|agency=Associated Press |date=12 July 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> A third unexploded vest was later found.<ref name="aljaz">[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2010/07/201071362446995742.html English.aljazeera.net]. English.aljazeera.net (13 July 2010). Retrieved on 6 July 2011.</ref>
