{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}} {{Infobox cricket tour | series_name = Pakistan in England 2006 | team1_image = Flag of Pakistan.svg | team1_name = Pakistan | team2_image = Flag of England.svg | team2_name = England | from_date = 1 July | to_date = 10 September 2006 | team1_captain = [[Inzamam-ul-Haq]] | team2_captain = [[Andrew Strauss]] | no_of_tests = 4 | team1_tests_won = 0 | team2_tests_won = 3 | team1_tests_most_runs = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] (631) | team2_tests_most_runs = [[Andrew Strauss]] (444) | team1_tests_most_wickets = [[Umar Gul]] (18) | team2_tests_most_wickets = [[Steve Harmison]] (20) | player_of_test_series = [[Mohammad Yousuf (cricket)|Mohammad Yousuf]] and [[Andrew Strauss]] | no_of_ODIs = 5 | team1_ODIs_won = 2 | team2_ODIs_won = 2 | team1_ODIs_most_runs = [[Younis Khan]] (215) | team2_ODIs_most_runs = [[Ian Bell]] (227) | team1_ODIs_most_wickets = [[Shoaib Akhtar]] (9) | team2_ODIs_most_wickets = [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] (7) | player_of_ODI_series = [[Younis Khan]] | no_of_twenty20s = 1 | team1_twenty20s_won = 1 | team2_twenty20s_won = 0 | team1_twenty20s_most_runs = [[Mohammad Hafeez]] (46) | team2_twenty20s_most_runs = [[Marcus Trescothick]] (53) | team1_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] (3) | team2_twenty20s_most_wickets = [[Stuart Broad]] (2) | player_of_twenty20_series = [[Shahid Afridi]] }} The Pakistani cricket team toured England in the [[2006 English cricket season]], following [[England cricket team|England]]'s [[English cricket team in Pakistan in 2005–06|winter tour of Pakistan]] where [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] had won a three-Test series 2–0 and the ODI series 4–1. As a result of this series, Pakistan rose two spots to be ranked second in the world Test rankings before this series, and England dropped to third after the 12 July annual update of the [[ICC Test Championship]]. The series was marred by a [[ball-tampering]] controversy on the fourth day of the Fourth Test, which culminated in Pakistan refusing to take the field after the tea interval in protest to a contentious decision by the umpires to penalise the Pakistani team for what they believed were acts of ball-tampering. This led the umpires to award the game to England, who thus won the Test series 3–0. In 2008, the ICC controversially declared the result of the final Test as a draw, altering the scoreline to 2–0; however, after criticism, not least by the MCC, this was subsequently reversed in February 2009 and the result restored as an England victory.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{cite news |title=Result U-turn for 2006 Oval Test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7863464.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=1 February 2009 }}</ref>
